"/> I don't blame you for not signing your name.

The exception to my enjoyment of almost any auction is one where I
discover the auctioneer lied to me. I will not attend any other
auction by that person. I don't mean the guy who holds up an
obviously modern, bad dish and chuckles &quot;Could be Spode!&quot; but the
one who deliberately misrepresents. You have a responsibility to
both the seller and the buyer, and if those &quot;co-sighners&quot; and
consigners ask you to lie, you are unindicted co-conspirators in fraud.

This is not to let off the buyer who didn't bother to examine what
he or she bought and whines &quot;you didn't tell me there was a crack.&quot;
You don't have to say everything you know. But if you lie, you are
a criminal who just hasn't been convicted yet. And the man or woman
who tries always to describe objects accurately is the one I come back
to again and again. If you lie, you get my money once. If you tell
the truth, you get my money regularly, for years. Which benefits you
more in the long run?

Tish Lehman (p ... @umich.edu)

Reply
</POST>



